The branches are created for each pull request by our `git fetch` refspec. I messed up the refspec a bit, caused a bunch of breakage, and then fixed the refspec, which passed through a brief breakage again.

In both directions, the biggest source of trouble was that the old branches pulled down by a prior refspec conflicted with new branches pulled by the new refspec.

It is unlikely that we actually want to change this much, so this isn't urgent. But we might as well remove this source of error / inflexibility. Otherwise, such a change generally requires wiping all workspaces (or removing the git branches one way or another).

I don't think there is a downside to this PR.
